Object Dictionary are important to keep your application loosly coupled, see : https://www.luos.io/blog/why-is-standardized-data-so-important-in-embedded-systems
see documentation : https://www.luos.io/docs/luos-technology/message/object-dictionary
see concerned folder : https://github.com/Luos-io/luos_engine/tree/main/engine/OD
To make Object Dictionary useful we need to be sure that users never directly write on OD (Object Dictionary) variables. If they do that the code become unsafe because the value will be stored with an unknown unit(or only known by the developer). OD structures should be always written using the dedicated functions forcing users to specify the used unit.
To do that I propose to modify the OD structure by adding a layer with a reserved var.
For example, instead of :
typedef float angular_position_t;

We should do:
typedef struct{
    float private;
} angular_position_t;

This way, to access the value, users have to do My_var.private = 10. This should convince them not to and to use functions instead.
All the functions of the OD will be able to use the private var to write or return a converted value.









